h3. Issue Summary
Selecting a scope of >5000 issues for a plan does not block from creation if the exceeding number is collapsed

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Create a project;
# Create 10 Epics;
# Create 5000 issues, distribute _some_ across the epics but not all
# Attempt to create a new plan using the project as the filter;
# In the Scope Selection view, leave the hierarchy level as *Epic*;
# Note that the epics and the "Issues without Parent issue" have arrows to be expanded;
# Click to create the plan;

h3. Expected Results
The plan does not get created because it is expected to now allot for more than 5000 issues at the moment of scope selection. [Reference|https://confluence.atlassian.com/advancedroadmapsserver/creating-your-plans-970267321.html].

h3. Actual Results
The plan gets created for as long as the collapsed sections do not get expanded.

If they are expanded, a warning in the screen saying that there are too many issues in the selection is displayed.

h3. Workaround

# Change the hierarchy level to the level that has the most issues.
# Configure the [loading limits to allow for more or less than the default values|https://community.atlassian.com/t5/Advanced-Roadmaps-questions/Re-Issue-limit-in-Portfolio/qaq-p/701142/comment-id/897#M897]

Our Documentation at "[Creating and deleting plans|https://confluence.atlassian.com/advancedroadmapsserver/creating-and-deleting-plans-802170502.html" should explicitly explain that the list of issues presented for selection are only the unresolved ones. 
Users get confused about why some of the already done stories are not listed when they do compare all the stories belonging to an Epic using Jira with all the stories listed at the Plan view.

{quote}
Confirming the scope
You can refine the list of issues to be included in your plan. To remove any issues you don't want to include in your plan, clear the checkboxes for these issues, and click Next.
{quote}

h3. Issue Summary
Users without the Schedule Issues permission can still commit Due Date values

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Revoke the *Schedule issues* permission from an user in a given project;
# Grant the *Advanced Roadmaps User* permission in the tool;
# Import an issue from the project in step #1 to the plan;
# As the user _without_ permission to schedule issues, set a value to *Due Date*;
# Commit the changes;

h3. Expected Results
User is unable to commit the changes as they do not have permissions to schedule issues.

h3. Actual Results
User is able to commit the changes and alter the Due Date value;

h3. Workaround
If the user is absolutely not allowed to perform this change, make them part of the *Restricted Users* group instead to prevent them from committing.

h3. Issue Summary

Sharing an iframe to embed a Program ships the incorrect JSPA file
h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Create a program;
 # Access the program;
 # Select *Share* and copy the embeddable object;
 # Include it in the target HTML file;

h3. Expected Results

The program is embedded to the target page;
h3. Actual Results

Jira returns a UI redressing error.
{noformat}
"To help protect the security of information you enter into this website, the publisher of this content does not allow it to be displayed in a frame."
{noformat}
h3. Workaround

Jira is providing an incorrect URL for the embeddable object. 
 # From the iframe, locate *{{/secure/PortfolioReportView.jspa}}*
 # **Replace *{{PortfolioReportView.jspa}}* with *{{PortfolioEmbeddedReportView.jspa}}*

h3. Issue Summary

Rolled-up data should display values based on filters and groups
h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Create an epic and four different children issues;
 # Give 5 points to each children issue;
 # Select to *Roll-up* values;
 # Assign issue_1 and issue_2 to team_A;
 # Assign issue_3 and issue_4 to team_B;
 # Apply a filter that looks up for team_A only;

h3. Expected Results

Rolled-up values for the epic should display 10 story points as the filter only includes two issues;
h3. Actual Results

Rolled-up values include the total of 20 points;
h3. Suggestion:

Add an option (checkmark if you will) to enable showing *all* of the rolled-up values regardless of the filter as well as an option to view only rolled-up values for entries picked up by the filter.

h3. Summary: Modifying a Sub-tasks team field from Software Boards cause inconsistencies

h3. Steps to replicate:
# Create a kanban board that filters by *team*;
# Give an user permissions to *edit issues* in the project 
# Revoke permissions to commit to plans (Plan Permissions > Edit plan);
# Create a Story and assign the this board's team to it;
# Commit the changes in JPO;
# Create a sub-task _after_ assigning the team to its parent's;
# * Note that the team field is empty for the sub-task;
# Expand the issue detail view for the parent task and scroll down to subtasks, note the message saying "1 sub-task is being filtered by the board's Saved Filter"
# Access the children task and re-assign it to the correct team;# 
# * Note that it shows up in the board
# Make any changes that would reindex the sub-task (or trigger a locked reindex)

h6. Expected results:
# The sub-task keeps its assignment of the team
# Or the sub-task pulls the team information from its parent (since JPO rolls the value down to sub-tasks)

h6. Actual results:
The sub-task loses the parent value and the sub-task is once more filtered from the board.

h3. Workaround:
Re-assign the team from the Plan view and commit the changes in Portfolio instead.

The permission for *Portfolio restricted user* states:
{quote}
Can perform the same tasks as Portfolio user; however *restricted users can only save changes to Jira for the plans for which they have edit permissions*
{quote}

This is incorrect as restricted users _cannot_ make changes to Jira Software regardless of having the edit permission. The [Permissions in Portfolio for Jira|https://confluence.atlassian.com/jiraportfolioserver/permissions-in-portfolio-for-jira-934719058.html] state the information correctly:
{quote}
However, even if restricted users are able to edit issue details in the plans, they cannot save these changes in Jira.
{quote}
